<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="2940" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[533,790,1107,1163]" box="[576,747,1139,1163]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">
(
<figureCitation box="[583,710,1139,1163]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1025,1044]" captionTargetBox="[128,1173,163,986]" captionTargetId="figure-110@5.[125,1173,133,989]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Lycaenid butterfly species investigated showing male dorsal wing surfaces. (A) Penaincisalia aurulenta Johnson, 1990 (Peru: PN Huascarán, Quebrada Demanda; HNHM); (B) Penaincisalia perezi Bálint, 2001 (Peru: PN Husacarán; Llanganuco; HNHM paratype); (C) Penaincisalia culminicola (Staudinger, 1894) (Peru: PNB Huascarán, Llanganuco; HNHM); (D) Thecloxurina loxurina (Felder and Felder, 1865) (Ecuador: Carchi, Res. Forest. Golondrinas; HNHM); (E) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Zamora, Cord. Lagunillas; HNHM); (F) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Azuay, Cuenca; HNHM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219996" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219996/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figures 1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[722,737,1139,1163]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[138,198,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-209@8.[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia perezi scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovel-shaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) low longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs, open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures; (C) moderate longitudinal ridges, curved cross-ribs, pepper-pot layers; (D) high longitudinal ridges, v-shaped cross ribs, small circular opening in microcell abyss." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5220000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5220000/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">3</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[138,1185,1205,1423]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">
The dorsal colour is vivid Magenta Orange with Ecclesiastic Purple iridescence (
<figureCitation box="[146,264,1237,1261]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1025,1044]" captionTargetBox="[128,1173,163,986]" captionTargetId="figure-110@5.[125,1173,133,989]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Lycaenid butterfly species investigated showing male dorsal wing surfaces. (A) Penaincisalia aurulenta Johnson, 1990 (Peru: PN Huascarán, Quebrada Demanda; HNHM); (B) Penaincisalia perezi Bálint, 2001 (Peru: PN Husacarán; Llanganuco; HNHM paratype); (C) Penaincisalia culminicola (Staudinger, 1894) (Peru: PNB Huascarán, Llanganuco; HNHM); (D) Thecloxurina loxurina (Felder and Felder, 1865) (Ecuador: Carchi, Res. Forest. Golondrinas; HNHM); (E) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Zamora, Cord. Lagunillas; HNHM); (F) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Azuay, Cuenca; HNHM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219996" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219996/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figure 1B</figureCitation>
). The scales are tile- or shovel-shaped with a uniformly toothed anterior margin. The length/width ratio of the tile-shaped scales is 3/1 (150/ 
<quantity box="[953,1030,1267,1293]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
); the shovelshaped scales are shorter, the length/width ratio is 2/1 (100/ 
<quantity box="[841,919,1300,1326]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
). The dentation of the tile-shaped scales is more pronounced while the dentation of the shovel-shaped scales is far less prominent (
<figureCitation box="[322,443,1367,1391]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[138,198,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-209@8.[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia perezi scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovel-shaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) low longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs, open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures; (C) moderate longitudinal ridges, curved cross-ribs, pepper-pot layers; (D) high longitudinal ridges, v-shaped cross ribs, small circular opening in microcell abyss." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5220000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5220000/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figure 3A</figureCitation>
). We found 
<specimenCount box="[585,709,1367,1391]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" type="generic" typeStatus="types">three types</specimenCount>
of scale microstructures, which suggest a transformation series (see Discussion):
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[138,1185,1464,1684]" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">
1. The longitudinal ridges are low, showing flutes on the longitudinal ridges, the cross ribs are straight. The space between the cross ribs is approximately 
<quantity box="[963,1045,1494,1520]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
; but highly variable, there are larger and smaller ratios. The widely open microcells are rectangular with fragmented nanostructures, the trabeculae and the lower scale membrane can be clearly seen (
<figureCitation box="[332,452,1594,1618]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[125,185,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-186@7.[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia aurulenta scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figure 2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[138,1185,1464,1684]" lastBlockId="7.[125,1172,1025,1247]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="2940" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">
2. The longitudinal ridges are moderate with flutes, which with curved cross ribs form rectangular-shaped deeper-laying microcells. Spaces between cross ribs are approximately 
<quantity box="[339,422,1025,1051]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
, and regular. The microcell openings are circular and pepper-pot nanostructures can be seen through the microcell openings (
<figureCitation box="[875,997,1059,1083]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[138,198,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-209@8.[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia perezi scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovel-shaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) low longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs, open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures; (C) moderate longitudinal ridges, curved cross-ribs, pepper-pot layers; (D) high longitudinal ridges, v-shaped cross ribs, small circular opening in microcell abyss." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5220000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5220000/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940">Figure 3C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940" startId="7.[125,185,910,929]" targetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1173,910,982]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940">
Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1990" box="[547,752,910,929]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Penaincisalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurulenta">
<emphasis box="[547,752,910,929]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940">Penaincisalia aurulenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,1172,1025,1247]" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940">
3. The longitudinal ridges with flutes are high and the cross ribs are v-shaped and form rectangular, very narrow, almost completely closed microcells with a single circular opening at the bottom. The spaces between the cross ribs are less than 
<quantity box="[1021,1104,1156,1182]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
; their sequence is regular. Pepper-pot nanostructures can be seen beneath the openings (
<figureCitation box="[176,299,1223,1247]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[138,198,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-209@8.[138,1186,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia perezi scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovel-shaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) low longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs, open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures; (C) moderate longitudinal ridges, curved cross-ribs, pepper-pot layers; (D) high longitudinal ridges, v-shaped cross ribs, small circular opening in microcell abyss." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5220000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5220000/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="2940">Figure 3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
